1.2. CONVERGENCE OF FOURIER SERIES 7
Theorem 2.2: Pointwise Fourier convergence
If a function f is nice enough (piecewise-smooth and 2π-periodic) then its
Fourier series converges point wise to f.
Piece-wise continuous is a milder condition than continuity. If f is piecewise-
continuous and you pick any interval I, then f only has ﬁnitely many discontinuities
in I and these discontinuities have all be jump discontinuities (and perhaps also re-
movable discontinuities). We don’t want crazy oscillation like sin 1/x or blowing up
to inﬁnity like 1/x. We want to be able to take the integral (area under the curve)
and talk about inner product!
Another way to describe piecewise-continuous function f is to say that we can
partition the domain into open intervals, where f is continuous on each of the
intervals. So the only potential sources of discontinuities come from the endpoints.
Figure 1.1:
Recall that a smooth function is one that has continuous derivative. Similarly,
we deﬁne a piecewise-smooth function as one that is smooth in any open interval
partition. The prototypical picture for piecewise-smooth f is a smooth curve except
for some jumps (where f is discontinuous) and corners (where f
0
is discontinuous).
Note that at corners x of f, the limit of f
0
from the left and the right diﬀer so we
can arbitrarily deﬁne f
0
(x) = 0 for example.
Now, suppose that f is periodic and piecewise-smooth so it has derivative. Fur-
ther, suppose that f
0
is also piece-wise smooth (the equivalent condition for this
is f is continuous) so that f
0
also has convergent Fourier expansion. Then, the
Fourier series of f
0
is obtained by diﬀerentiating that of f term by term.
Our recurrent condition is that f is periodic, continuous and piece-wise smooth
to avoid pathology like Weierstrass function which is continuous everywhere but
diﬀerentiable no where.

1.3 Odd-Even Extension
So far, we have dealt with function that is deﬁned on R and is 2π-periodic. What
about those that deﬁned on a ﬁnite interval, say [0, 1], and is periodic but with a
diﬀerent period?
First, we explain how to extend f deﬁned on [0, π]. We have two choices: even
or odd extension. With even extension, we set
f(−θ) = f(θ)
for θ ∈ [−π, 0]. The corresponding Fourier series will only consist of cosines (no
sines) since cosines are even function (even functions are symmetric around y-axis.
Think even power polynomial like f(x) = x
2
). With odd extension, the function is
extended to be symmetric around the origin.
f(−θ) = −f(θ)
for θ ∈ [−π, 0]. The corresponding Fourier series will only consist of sines. Odd
functions think of f(x) = x.
The odd/even extensions of the original function f will have the same continuity
property as f except possibly at points x = nπ when these pieces are glued together.

1.5. STURM-LIOUVILLE PROBLEM 15
Theorem 5.1: Spectral theorem for Sturm-Lioville
If we have a regular Sturm-Liouville problem, then
• All eigenvalues are real
• Eigenfunctions corresponding to distinct eigenvalues are orthogonal
• Eigenspace for any λ is at most 2-dimensional. With separated boundary
conditions, it’s always 1-dimensional.
The ﬁrst two are just the analogs of spectral theorem in linear algebra. The last one
comes from existence and uniqueness of ODE. For any constant c

An important theorem: for regular SL problem, the eigenfunctions form an
orthonormal basis. Eigenvalues are countable. (theorem 3.10)
